			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I've been out of the hacker circuit for a couple of years. Where can I get a copy of this?
<br />

<br />
The source for the leak appears to be Mainsoft which makes a win/unix product. 
<br />

<br />
As for the complaint about more viruses and worms: if windows had been open source, they would have been fixed by now. <a href="http://www.cert.org/advisories/CA-2001-01.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Here is an example of a closed source product with an incurable security defect, only discovered when the source was made open, 7 years after the code was on the marketplace</a>. Because windows and sql server are closed source, there is no way that you can be certain that equivalent backdoors do not already exist in those products.
<br />

<br />
An equivalent hissy fit was made when <a href="http://www.crypto.com/masterkey.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Matt Blaze published a paper describing a flaw in the master key system used in the US for over 100 years and kept hushed up by the locksmithing community</a>.
<br />

<br />
Security by obscurity is no security at all. And that is the security you get when you use closed source software. You have to trust people with competing agendas and pretend that they are telling the truth. Cynical observation has shown that coverups and false claims of protecting security are used to hide stupidity from the general public. The dark side already knows how to break in. It is the law abiding that need to understand the risks and be able to make their own decisions on the matter. Highschool joyriders, Saturn engineers, Police and crooks already know how to hotwire a Saturn with only a pair of scissors. Saturn owners do not, but should know that.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
