			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				That won't do you any good. The code code in XP is mostly (I'd say 85%) Windows 2000 code. The major changes for XP were in the user interface and hardware interface. Why else do you think that an exploit for a network overflow causes a patch to be released for NT, 2K, XP, and 2K3? They share the majority of their codebase, and a bug in one is a bug in all. 
<br />

<br />
They'll have to rewrite more Longhorn code than they like because of this leak, I'll wager. It's high time for a ground up reworking of some core windows systems anyway, and their "focus on security" will benefit from it greatly.
<br />

<br />
Still waiting for some programmer somewhere to check the code and give us a write up on how bad it really is. I think this may end up embarrasing Microsoft in more ways than just security. Their codebase may end up looking like amateur hacking compared to open source projects, and that'll limit the number of bad things they can get away saying about open source. In particular, it'll put an end to the "closed source is more secure" and "open source doesn't produce projects as professional and well written as closed source" arguments.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
