				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=49973&amp;sid=dbc92e0a9c1d458a22c1509323ff5db6"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				The source of the leak was a Microsoft partner known as Mainsoft. Mainsoft makes Windows applications compile and run natively under Linux (yes, ALL of Microsoft's applications). The code was apparently on some protected developer box, which was inherited without a clean format by someone lower on the chain in the company who recognized it for what it was and let it loose on the net. Whoever the leaker was, he's in for a world of hurt when Microsoft finds him. He's going to get a treatment that makes Mitnick's entire case look like saturday detention by comparison. Technically Mainsoft and the people working for them are responsible for the damage, and can be sued for negligence. Beyond that, however, Microsoft has no legal options. There is simply nothing they can do.
<br />

<br />
It was about 15% of the total Win2000 codebase (all core components), and 100% of the NT4 codebase. It is approximately 3 years old, dating back to the release of Win2000 SP1. The code changes so little with each revision however that it has a lot of relevance on code in all current versions of windows.
<br />

<br />
There have been code leaks in the past, but they were shut down fast and never really made it out into the wild. This leak has penetrated all the way out to usenet, so everyone and anyone anywhere can get it. It's the worst code leak in history for Microsoft, because you don't have to be "in" with people in the pirating scene to get a copy like their two or three previous leaks. You can find it on any p2p network with a 5 minute search.
<br />

<br />
Microsoft has officially and permanetly lost all trade secret claims to this code because of this leak.
<br />

<br />
Keep in mind they are sharing the ENTIRE codebase with China right now in an attempt to get them to abandon their idea of making Red Flag Linux. I guarantee you that at some point, China is going to leak the whole ball of wax. Microsoft can't do a thing to them if they do it, and neither can the US Government. It's really just a matter of time.
<br />

<br />
Frankly at this point Microsoft should just cave in and develop themselves a good open source license and join in the fun. It'd be the best thing they could do right now. It'd also put a permanent end to their ability to obfuscate standards, which is the only real reason they won't do it. I think they'll eventually get forced into that position, and it'll permanently level the playing field if it happens. They are the only major OS vendor who is not open source right now. Linux, Apple, and nearly all brands of Unix are open sourced in one way or another at this point.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
